@Node Introduction RndPat.guide/Introduction

@{u}@{b}Introduction@{ub}@{uu}

Yet another Workbench background picture selector. Oh well, as usual, there
wasn't any satisfactory solution to a problem, so I hacked one up.

Until recently, I had used the CGWBPattern program, which did a good job,
though I really only needed the random part of it. However, I bought
DirOpus 5.5 and tried it as a Workbench replacement, and I suspected
CGWBPattern wouldn't work any more (I must admit I didn't test it).

So, I was left with a fixed background picture. A bit boring, I thought, so
I checked Aminet for a program to fix it. They were all large (for what
they did), and generally didn't behave quite the way I wanted.

Since I had some other code (from PicBoot) that could be used here, it was
a fairly quick matter of writing the extra code needed to wrap this program
up, so I did that. A couple of hours later, the program was finished (well,
almost ;).

As of Opus Magellan, Opus supports a new way of specifying background
patterns, that does not use the normal WBPattern preferences file. These
patterns can be changed by using an ARexx command. As I had some code for
sending ARexx messages as well, I added support for this Opus future. This
is what the new program OpusRndPat does, which requires Opus Magellan (5.6x
or higher) to function properly.

@EndNode


@Node Requirements RndPat.guide/Requirements

@{u}@{b}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

RndPat and OpusRndPat should work with any Amiga with OS 3.0 or higher.

It should be fairly easy to lower the system requirements to 2.04, as the
only 3.0 specific call is ExAllEnd(). However, I haven't bothered to fix
that. ;)

Since the current time is used as the random number seed, it is preferable
to have a battery backed up clock for best operation.

Note that the Opus function OpusRndPat uses requires OS 3.0 or higher, and
is only available in Opus Magellan (5.6x or higher).

@EndNode


@Node Installation RndPat.guide/Installation

@{u}@{b}Installation@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}RndPat@{ub}

RndPat doesn't provide any fancy GUI, installation script or similar, so
you'll need to do some work yourself. Its not much though; basically two
things are needed:

	1) Copy RndPat to somewhere convenient (within the command search
	   path is a good idea. An example of this is "C:").

	2) Add a line to your S:User-Startup file. The one I currently use
	   looks like this:

	   C:RndPat Pics:WB/Workbench Pics:WB/Windows

	   See @{"Usage" Link Usage} for details.

@{b}OpusRndPat@{ub}

OpusRndPat is a bit different, hut there are two basic steps here as well:

	1) Copy OpusRndPat to somewhere convenient (within the command
	   search path is a good idea. An example of this is "C:", or maybe
	   "DOpus5:C/").

	2) Add OpusRndPat to your startup script in Opus, with proper
	   arguments. See the Opus manual for details about this.

Perhaps you'll prefer to copy this guide somewhere as well.

@EndNode


@Node Usage RndPat.guide/Usage

@{u}@{b}Usage@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}RndPat@{ub}

RndPat has the following template:

	WORKBENCH,WINDOW,SCREEN,FILE/K,NOREMAP/S,SHOW/S

@{b}WORKBENCH@{ub}
	This argument specifies the path to scan for the main Workbench
	pattern picture. Default is no path (which means that no picture
	will be set).

@{b}WINDOW@{ub}
	This argument specifies the path to scan for the pattern picture
	for the Workbench drawer windows. Default is no path (which means
	that no picture will be set).

@{b}SCREEN@{ub}
	This argument specifies the path to scan for the pattern picture
	for the Workbench screen. Default is no path (which means that no
	picture will be set).

@{b}FILE@{ub}
	This argument specifies the name of the preferences file to be
	created. The default is "Env:Sys/wbpattern.prefs", which is where
	Workbench (or rather, IPrefs) looks for its configuration.

@{b}NOREMAP@{ub}
	This argument causes the Workbench to not remap the picture after
	it is loaded. Only use this if the pictures are saved with the same
	palette as the Workbench screen, or the result will (probably) not
	look very good.

	Directory Opus 5.5 seems to ignore this flag, and will always remap
	the picture.

@{b}SHOW@{ub}
	Rather than generating a new prefs file, this option will cause the
	specified FILE (or the default) to be read, and RndPat will display
	some information about the settings found. Thus, you don't need to
	start WBPattern just to see what RndPat selected.

@{b}OpusRndPat@{ub}

OpusRndPat has the following template:

	DESKTOP,LISTER=WINDOW,REQUESTER,PRECISION/K,CENTER/S,VERBOSE/S,
	PORT/K,DELAY/K/N

@{b}DESKTOP@{ub}
	This argument specifies the path to scan for the main Opus Desktop
	pattern picture. Default is no path (which means that any current
	picture will not be changed).

@{b}LISTER@{ub}, @{b}WINDOW@{ub}
	This argument specifies the path to scan for the pattern picture
	for the Opus lister windows. Default is no path (which means that
	any current picture will not be changed).

@{b}REQUESTER@{ub}
	This argument specifies the path to scan for the pattern picture
	for Opus requesters. Default is no path (which means that any
	current picture will not be changed).

@{b}PRECISION@{ub}
	This argument specifies the remapping precision Opus should use for
	the pictures. This argument is passed to Opus without any parsing
	(the argument is passed as the PRECISION argument for the
	SetAsBackground command). Default is IMAGE.

@{b}CENTER@{ub}
	This argument specifies that the pattern should be centered rather
	than tiled.

@{b}VERBOSE@{ub}
	Display the backgrounds set, if the Opus did not return any error.

@{b}PORT@{ub}
	The name of the ARexx port to send the messages to. Default is
	DOPUS.1.

@{b}DELAY@{ub}
	Current versions of Opus have a small problem with the quick
	sequence of ARexx commands sent by OpusRndPat. It seems like it
	forgets to load the patterns set while the first one is being
	loaded. With this argument you can tell OpusRndPat to wait a little
	between each command.

	The value is number of @{i}ticks,@{ui} and there are 50 tics per
	second. So, to wait half a second between each command, specify 25,
	to wait one second, specify 50. If no value is specified, or if the
	value is less than one, no wait will occur. Default is no value.

OpusRndPat does not have a SHOW argument like RndPat. You'll have to open
the Enviroment settings window to see which patterns are being used.

@{i}Note:@{ui}	The WORKBENCH, WINDOW, SCREEN, DESKTOP, LISTER and
	REQUESTER paths all supports patterns. Simply enter the pattern
	where the file name usually would have been. RndPat and OpusRndPat
	will check the final part of the path, and if it seems to be a
	pattern, it is assumed to be one. If you specify the name of an
	existing file, that file will simply be used as is.

	Example: To random select among all pictures ending with ".png" in
	the drawer "Pics:WBPatterns", enter "Pics:WBPatterns/#?.png".

@EndNode


@Node SourceNotes "RndPat.guide/Source notes"

@{u}@{b}Source notes@{ub}@{uu}

RndPat was compiled using SAS/C V6.58, using the provided SCOPTIONS file.
The few compiler specific things that are used (including some "#pragma
msg":s) are (read: should be) located in the header file.

The code was compiled with most warnings enabled, so most other Amiga
compilers should be able to compile it with only minimal changes.

The make file (DMakeFile) is written for the DICE 3 DMake. DMake has some
features I like, so I haven't bothered to learn SMake yet (though SMake has
some nice features as well). ;)

The tab stop size used is the standard 8 (yep, I like it that way ;).

@EndNode


@Node History "RndPat.guide/Program history"

@{u}@{b}Program history, RndPat@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Version 1.0@{ub}:
	Initial release.

@{b}Version 1.1@{ub}: (Not released)
	If a specified path refers to an existing file, that file will be
	used as is, rather than assumed to be a drawer. Makes it easier to
	test a specific backdrop.

@{b}Version 1.2@{ub}:
	RndPat:
		Added an error message if the template was wrong.

		Split the source into a couple of modules.

		Called OpenIFF() twice on the same IFFHandle.

@{u}@{b}Program history, OpusRndPat@{ub}@{uu}

@{b}Version 1.0@{ub}:
	Initial release.

@EndNode


